04285nam a22005655i 9780226537344DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265373447 a10.7208/97802265373442doi  a(DE-B1597)521377  a(OCoLC)1028979506  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBR115.H6bL48 2018eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a289.9/4086609732231 aLewin, Ellen, eauthor.10aFilled with the Spirit :bSexuality, Gender, and Radical Inclusivity in a Black Pentecostal Church Coalition /cEllen Lewin. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b3 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tInvocation: The Anthropology Ministry -- t1 "I've Been 'Buked": The Double Consciousness of Being LGBT and Black -- t2. "Lead Me, Guide Me": The Charisma of Bishop Flunder -- t3. "Just as I Am": Revealing Authentic Selves -- t4. "Old-Time Religion": Invoking Memory -- t5. "What a Fellowship": Radically Inclusive Futures -- tBenediction: Continuities and Departures -- tNotes -- tReferences Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2001, a collection of open and affirming churches with predominantly African American membership and a Pentecostal style of worship formed a radically new coalition. The group, known now as the Fellowship of Affirming Ministries or TFAM, has at its core the idea of "radical inclusivity": the powerful assertion that everyone, no matter how seemingly flawed or corrupted, has holiness within. Whether you are LGBT, have HIV/AIDS, have been in prison, abuse drugs or alcohol, are homeless, or are otherwise compromised and marginalized, TFAM tells its people, you are one of God's creations. In Filled with the Spirit, Ellen Lewin gives us a deeply empathetic ethnography of the worship and community central to TFAM, telling the story of how the doctrine of radical inclusivity has expanded beyond those it originally sought to serve to encompass people of all races, genders, sexualities, and religious backgrounds. Lewin examines the seemingly paradoxical relationship between TFAM and traditional black churches, focusing on how congregations and individual members reclaim the worship practices of these churches and simultaneously challenge their authority. The book looks closely at how TFAM worship is legitimated and enhanced by its use of gospel music and considers the images of food and African American culture that are central to liturgical imagery, as well as how understandings of personal authenticity tie into the desire to be filled with the Holy Spirit. Throughout, Lewin takes up what has been mostly missing from our discussions of race, gender, and sexuality-close attention to spirituality and faith.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aAfrican American sexual minoritiesxReligious life. 0aHomosexualityxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aPentecostalism. 4aAfrican American culture. 4aLGBT religion. 4aPentecostalism. 4acharisma. 4aradical inclusivity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226537344423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226537344.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles